  	<title>Encoding</title>
  
  	<table>
  		<title>ENCODING</title>
  		<tgroup cols="4" align="left" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
  			<thead>
  				<row>
  					<entry align="center">Parameter Name</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Data Type</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Possible Values</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Default</entry>	
  				</row>
  			</thead>
  			<tbody>
  				<row>
  					<entry>ENCODING</entry>
  					<entry>String</entry>
  					<entry></entry>
  					<entry>UTF-8</entry>
  				</row>
  			</tbody>
  		</tgroup>
  	</table>
  	<itemizedlist>
  		<listitem>
  			<para>
  				With this parameter you can set the encoding for the command line/console of the machine 
  				on which your external command is executed
  			</para>
  		</listitem>
  		<listitem>
  			<para>
  				Possible values can be e.g. UTF-8 or 850.
  			</para>
  		</listitem>
  		<listitem>
  			<para>
  				You can use e.g <emphasis>chcp</emphasis> on Windows machines to find out the encoding 
  				of this very machine.
  			</para>
  		</listitem>
  		<listitem>
  			<para>
  				The encoding is especially important when your external command contains special characters,
  				mutated vowels etc.
  			</para>
  		</listitem>
  	</itemizedlist>
</section>